===Etymology===
Likely to be from same source as Old English (Anglo-Saxon) ''[[bita]]'' and ''[[bite#Old English|bite]]'', or from those words themselves; the monetary sense derives from Caribbean or South US practice of cutting Spanish dollars into eighths.

===Noun===
'''bit''' (''plural'' '''[[bits]]''')

#<!--DefA-->A piece of metal placed in a horse's mouth and connected to reins to direct the animal. 
#<!--DefB-->A rotary cutting tool fitted to a drill, used to make holes. 
#<!--DefC-->An eighth of a dollar.
#:''A [[quarter]] is two bits.''
#<!--DefD-->(''dated UK'') A coin of a specified value.
#:''threepenny bit''
#<!--DefE-->A small piece of something.
#:''There were bits of paper all over the floor.''
#<!--DefE2-->A portion of something
#:''I'd like a big bit of cake, please.''
#<!--DefF-->(slang) A prison sentence.

